{"contentApi":{"id":"world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live","sectionId":"world","sectionName":"World news","webPublicationDate":1355760300000,"webTitle":"Newtown shooting: funerals to be held for victims – as it happened","webUrl":"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live","fields":{"trailText":"<p>Service to be held for youngest victim on Monday afternoon as Obama says 'we can't accept events like this as routine'. Follow the latest developments here</p>","headline":"Newtown shooting: funerals to be held for victims – as it happened","body":"<div id=\"block-50cfa5a395cb356c029eb0e6\" class=\"block is-summary\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T23:07:15.498Z\">6.07pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><h2 class=\"block-title\">Summary</h2><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>We're going to wrap up our <strong>live coverage</strong> for the day. <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live#block-50cf770bb5799fbf77759f56\">Funeral</a> <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live#block-50cf5adf95cb356c029eb0b2\">services</a> were held this afternoon for two boys killed in the Newtown shooting. Wake services for a third victim are planned for this evening. The town of Newtown will hold funerals for the next three days.&nbsp;Here's a summary of where things stand:</p><p>•<strong> New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg began a new push for gun control legislation with a press conference attended by dozens of family members of victims of gun violence.</strong> The mayor introduced a series of videos known as<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live#block-50cf670f95cb356c029eb0b4\"> Demand A Plan</a>, in which people talk about losing loved ones to gun violence and call for new laws.&nbsp;</p><p>•<strong> Governor Dan Malloy called for tougher federal gun laws including a ban on assault weapons and large ammunition clips. </strong>The <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live#block-50cf53c495cb356c029eb0b0\">discussion</a> of <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live#block-50cf95c2b5799fbf77759f79\">how politicians might</a> pass new gun laws gained momentum.</p><p>• <strong>Connecticut state police <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/us-news-blog/2012/dec/17/newtown-shootings-funerals-victims-live#block-50cf5f9a95cb356c029eb0b3\">said</a> the investigation would be exhaustive and take some time.</strong> The governor ordered that a vacant schoolhouse near Newtown be opened to take Sandy Hook students. The governor called for a statewide minute of silence for the victims on Friday morning.</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cfa1ef95cb356c029eb0e5\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T22:51:28.247Z\">5.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>Over the weekend <strong>Fox News</strong>&nbsp;producers and hosts were &quot;expressly forbidden from discussing gun control,&quot; New York Magazine <a href=\"http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2012/12/murdoch-wants-new-gun-laws-fox-news-not-so-much.html\">quotes</a> anonymous sources as saying:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>According to sources, David Clark, the executive producer in charge of Fox’s weekend coverage, gave producers instructions not to talk about gun-control policy on air. &quot;This network is not going there,” Clark wrote one producer on Saturday night, according to a source with knowledge of the exchange. The directive created a rift inside the network.&nbsp;</p></blockquote><p>Fox News of course is part of News Corp, where the boss, Rupert Murdoch, strongly favors &quot;bold leadership action&quot; on gun control. At least that's what the Rupert Murdoch on Twitter wants. It's unclear whether he's willing to risk the bottom line of Fox News by encouraging the network (or he could simply instruct them) to hew to basic journalistic praxis and cover what is a central aspect of the story at hand.</p><figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/rupertmurdoch/status/280114713688416256\"><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Nice words from POTUS on shooting tragedy, but how about some bold leadership action?</p>— Rupert Murdoch(@rupertmurdoch) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/rupertmurdoch/status/280114713688416256\" data-datetime=\"2012-12-16T00:58:46+00:00\">December 16, 2012</a></blockquote></figure><p>The author of the NY Mag piece, Gabriel Sherman, <a href=\"http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2012/12/murdoch-wants-new-gun-laws-fox-news-not-so-much.html\">notes</a> that the apparent omerta on gun control wasn't absolute, as&nbsp;<em>Fox News Sunday</em>&nbsp;host Chris Wallace had Democratic Senators Joe Lieberman and Dick Durbin on to talk about gun control.</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf9ca5b5799fbf77759f7a\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T22:28:54.115Z\">5.28pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>The Guardian's Matt Williams has&nbsp;been reaching out to <strong>pro-gun senators</strong> to ask them for comment on Friday's tragedy and whether new gun control laws are needed:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Of the 28 senators and members-elect approached – all of whom have been given an “A” grade from the National Rifle Association (NRA) for their pro-gun views - only one has given a response thus far, although incoming senator Ted Cruz's people said he is travelling and may speak to us later.</p><p>Which leaves Senator Richard Shelby as the only politician to respond. A spokesman for the senior Republican senator from Alabama said: “He believes we must consider any proposals very carefully.”</p><p>Although he made far briefer comments to the media today than those from Joe Manchin and Mark Warner – two Democrat senators with NRA “A” ratings who have suggested they are open to the new gun rules - Shelby appears to be the first pro-gun Republican to indicate a willingness to engage in a discussion.</p></blockquote><p>Update: Matt has just received a response via email from a spokesperson for Senator Johnny Isakson of Georgia. The senator says the attack &quot;should cause us to pause and take stock&quot; but he does not mention gun control or new gun laws. He does mention &quot;school security&quot;:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>First and foremost, I send my deepest condolences to the families of the victims of the school shooting in Newtown. This terrible tragedy and the other similar mass shootings in recent years should cause us to pause and take stock. After 9/11, we came together to see what we could do to prevent another attack. The work of the 9/11 Commission made flying safer and has helped us prevent another hijacking of a U.S. plane by terrorists.We should evaluate in a thoughtful process gun safety, mental health, school security and all other components that contributed to this horrendous act of violence.</p></blockquote></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T22:40:26.898Z\">at 5.40pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf95c2b5799fbf77759f79\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T21:59:31.035Z\">4.59pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>Why won't <strong>politicians vote</strong> for stricter gun laws? Because the National Rifle Association will trash them and they'll never win another election. The calculation may be brutal but there's a logic to it.</p><p>Except it's <strong>patently untrue</strong>: politicians who defy the NRA don't necessarily lose, and politicians who kowtow to the gun lobby don't necessarily win.&nbsp;</p><p>Even in states with large Republican populations, politicians who support gun control can win big. The New Republic's Nate Cohn <a href=\"https://twitter.com/electionate/statuses/280789298700251137\">points</a> to two cases:&nbsp;Tim Kaine has a rating of &quot;F&quot; from the NRA and just won a Virginia Senate election by 6 points; Bill Nelson also received an &quot;F&quot; and just won a Florida Senate election by 13 points. Here's a <a href=\"http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/the-buzz-florida-politics/content/nra-takes-aim-bill-nelson-new-pro-mack-mailer\">scan of a flier</a>&nbsp;in which the NRA attacks Nelson – it turns out ineffectually.</p><p>Senator Scott Brown of Massachusetts, meanwhile, <a href=\"http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/politics/2012/07/6292816/bloomberg-backs-scott-brown-nras-candidate-against-elizabeth-warren\">had an &quot;A&quot;</a> from the NRA before losing to Elizabeth Warren last month by 7 points.</p><p>Defying the NRA works in national elections, too. The NRA has never gone after a candidate like it did Barack Obama, Slate's Dave Weigel points out:&nbsp;</p><figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/daveweigel/status/280790209761796096\"><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\" data-in-reply-to=\"280790010989531136\"><p>@<a href=\"https://twitter.com/electionate\">electionate</a> Also, they went all out against Obama twice and he kicked their asses twice.</p>— daveweigel (@daveweigel) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/daveweigel/status/280790209761796096\" data-datetime=\"2012-12-17T21:42:57+00:00\">December 17, 2012</a></blockquote></figure><p>The Guardian's Harry J. Enten piles on:</p><figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/ForecasterEnten/status/280794631644512259\"><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Tom Harkin is another good example in IA where guns are a plenty and Dems do well despite pro-control stances</p>— Harry Enten (@ForecasterEnten) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ForecasterEnten/status/280794631644512259\" data-datetime=\"2012-12-17T22:00:31+00:00\">December 17, 2012</a></blockquote></figure><p>Update: Harry points to <a href=\"http://usliberals.about.com/od/Election2012Factors/a/Gun-Owners-As-Percentage-Of-Each-States-Population.htm\">this list</a> of states with a high proportion of gun owners:</p><p><strong>States with Extremely High Populations of Gun Owners&nbsp;</strong>(more than 50%):</p><p>1. Wyoming - 59.7%</p><p>2. Alaska - 57.8%</p><p>3. Montana - 57.7%</p><p>4. South Dakota - 56.6%</p><p>5. West Virginia - 55.4%</p><p>6. Mississippi - 55.3%</p><p>6. Idaho - 55.3%</p><p>6. Arkansas - 55.3%</p><p>9. Alabama - 51.7%</p><p>10. North Dakota - 50.7%</p></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T22:24:14.842Z\">at 5.24pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf8bd0b5799fbf77759f6c\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T21:17:05.185Z\">4.17pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>At the <strong>staging area</strong> after the Sandy Hook shooting there was a &quot;reluctance&quot; to tell parents their children had died, Governor Dan Malloy said, and so he took the decision to tell them.</p><p>&quot;It was evident to me that there was a reluctance to tell parents and loved ones that the person they were waiting for was not going to be going home,&quot; Malloy said.</p><p>&quot;So I made a decision that rather than relying on traditional, investigative policies ... I made the decision that to have that go on any longer was wrong.</p><p>&quot;I did it.&quot;&nbsp;</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf898a95cb356c029eb0d3\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T21:07:22.572Z\">4.07pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>Governor Dan Malloy calls for <strong>stricter gun laws,</strong> including an assault weapons ban of some kind and a ban on large ammunition magazines.</p><p>&quot;I support a person's opportunity to hunt, and to meet the strictest interpretation of the second amendment... beyond that, I think this thing has gotten way out of control,&quot; he said.</p><p>Connecticut actually has an assault weapons ban on the books, but&nbsp;&quot;in the absence of a federal framework... no state would be safe based on its own laws,&quot; Malloy said. &quot;That's why a [federal] assault weapons ban was so very important.&quot;</p><p>A federal ban on assault weapons was allowed to lapse in 2004.&nbsp;</p><p>&quot;I'm a big believer in hunting rights, a big believer in the second amendment, but the reality is that this has gone too far,&quot; the governor said.</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf889995cb356c029eb0d1\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T21:04:16.883Z\">4.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>In a news briefing still happening, Connecticut <strong>governor Dan Malloy</strong> said he attended Noah Pozner's funeral. The lieutenant governor attended the funeral of Jack Pinto.</p><p>&quot;There really are no words to describe&quot; the pain of the parents, Malloy said. &quot;You see little coffins and your heart has to ache.&quot;</p><p>Malloy said a statewide moment of silence would be observed on Friday, 21 December at 9.30am, exactly a week after the massacre began. He called on houses of worship to ring their bells 26 times for the victims.</p><p>The governor said&nbsp;he had issued an emergency declaration to open a surplus school in Monroe, Connecticut, to take students from Sandy Hook &quot;immediately.&quot;</p></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T21:24:26.053Z\">at 4.24pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf833d95cb356c029eb0cd\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T20:40:30.083Z\">3.40pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>The gunman in the Connecticut school shooting fired guns at <strong>shooting ranges</strong> over the past several years, but there's no evidence he did so recently, according to federal agents. The AP reports:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Debora Seifert, a spokeswoman for Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives, says Adam Lanza and his mother each fired at shooting ranges. They also visited ranges together.</p><p>But Seifert tells the AP that ATF investigators have no indication now &quot;that the shooter engaged in shooting activities in the past six months.&quot;</p></blockquote></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf81f595cb356c029eb0ca\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T20:35:02.263Z\">3.35pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>Writing in the New York Review of Books, Garry Wills <a href=\"http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2012/dec/15/our-moloch/\">sees</a> the gun as a terrible deity that American society sacrifices children to, &quot;<strong>our Moloch</strong>&quot;:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>That horror cannot be blamed just on one unhinged person. It was the sacrifice we as a culture made, and continually make, to our demonic god. We guarantee that crazed man after crazed man will have a flood of killing power readily supplied him. We have to make that offering, out of devotion to our Moloch, our god. The gun is our Moloch. We sacrifice children to him daily—sometimes, as at Sandy Hook, by directly throwing them into the fire-hose of bullets from our protected private killing machines, sometimes by blighting our children’s lives by the death of a parent, a schoolmate, a teacher, a protector.</p></blockquote><p>The <a href=\"http://www.nybooks.com/blogs/nyrblog/2012/dec/15/our-moloch/\">full piece is here</a>.</p></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T20:35:24.041Z\">at 3.35pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf7c72b5799fbf77759f5a\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T20:11:31.280Z\">3.11pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>YouTube user <a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/user/whoiswillo?feature=watch\">whoiswillo</a> has spliced footage of the last three presidents delivering speeches after <strong>three mass shootings</strong> at schools.</p><p>The footage is taken from President Bill Clinton's speech after the 1999 Columbine shooting, President George W. Bush's speech after the 2007 Virginia Tech shooting and President Barack Obama's speech after the Newtown shooting.</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf7a7c95cb356c029eb0bf\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T20:03:08.920Z\">3.03pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>The Guardian's Adam Gabbatt is in Fairfield, Connecticut, where a <strong>memorial service</strong> was held for Noah Pozner, 6.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>Just before 2pm people began to slowly file out of the funeral home where Noah Pozner's service took place. The door to the black hearse opened, and was closed. Police motorcycles led the procession away.</p><p>Mourners told of an emotional ceremony as family and friends said goodbye to the six-year-old.</p><p>Audrey Petschek, 48, has lived close to Sandy Hook school for over 20 years. &quot;I just think its important that everybody in Newtown is there to support the families,&quot; she said.</p><p>She said it had been a &quot;very personal and loving tribute&quot;.</p><p>Pozner's elder brother had spoken at the funeral, Petschek said. &quot;Just how he had an endless love for his brother. He's very strong right now. He's being remarkably strong.&quot;</p><p>Pozner's mother spoke too. &quot;She's obviously numb too,&quot; Petschek said. &quot;But, you know, a mother's love... It was hard to hear.&quot;</p></blockquote></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf770bb5799fbf77759f56\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T19:48:28.217Z\">2.48pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>The Guardian's Ed Pilkington is <strong>in Newtown,</strong> where a funeral was held for&nbsp;Jack Pinto, six, whose main passion had been the New York Giants American football team.</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>In photos, he was shown with an NY logo drawn on his face and &quot;Go Giants!&quot; tattooed in crayon on his hand. His favourite player was the receiver Victor Cruz, who played against the Atlanta Falcons on Sunday with &quot;Jack Pinto, My Hero&quot; written on his boots.</p><p>As the town of about 25,000 people braces itself for so many funerals – of the 20 children, the six teachers and teaching assistants, as well as those of the shooter Adam Lanza and his mother, Nancy, whom he killed before setting off for the school – residents and visitors have been setting up makeshift memorials as a focus for communal grief.</p><p>Sandy Hook fire house, where 20 sets of parents learned that their children would not be coming home, has become the main site of mourning. People drift to and from the growing memorial, some leaving flowers, others soft toys. Many just stand in silence.</p></blockquote><p>The full piece, including reporting by Adam Gabbatt in Fairfield,<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2012/dec/17/newtown-families-funerals-shooting-victims\">&nbsp;is here</a>.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf74d295cb356c029eb0b6\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T19:38:59.366Z\">2.38pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p><strong>Newtown grieves.</strong> A photo gallery of memorials&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gallery/2012/dec/17/newtown-funerals-victims-pictures\">is here</a>.</p><figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-713de84a-dbae-43c8-805a-e45c1191f706\"><img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2012/12/17/1355773059102/7b27ac8f-182b-49d0-b520-652e818635ca-460.jpeg\" alt=\"A hearse and family limousines for six-year-old shooting victim Jack Pinto rolls past a flag at half staff as the funeral procession heads through the historic district in Newtown, Conn., Monday, Dec. 17, 2012.\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /><figcaption>A hearse and family limousines for six-year-old shooting victim Jack Pinto rolls past a flag at half staff as the funeral procession heads through the historic district in Newtown, Conn., Monday, Dec. 17, 2012. Photograph: Charles Krupa/AP</figcaption></figure></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf670f95cb356c029eb0b4\" class=\"block is-key-event\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T19:04:10.718Z\">2.04pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><h2 class=\"block-title\">Bloomberg makes forceful call for gun control laws</h2><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>Calling for immediate action to stop America's string of mass shootings, New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg gathered dozens of family members of victims of fatal gun violence to stand behind him at a Monday&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yt-nEl55eXU\">news conference</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>&quot;If you think there's a lot of people here, that's because there's an awful lot of gun violence in this country,&quot; Bloomberg said.</p><p>The mayor said he intends to pressure the president and the Congress for new legislation, now, to get gun violence under control.</p><p>&quot;The president and Congress can and should address [gun control] at the same time they're reaching an agreement on avoiding the fiscal cliff,&quot; Bloomberg said. &quot;These things have nothing to do with each other. And if Congress and the president can't focus on two things at once, who on Earth did we elect?&quot;</p><p>As part of his visible new push on gun control, Bloomberg presented a set of 34 video statements by people who have lost loved ones to gun violence.</p><p>The message of each video, the mayor said,&nbsp;is the same:&nbsp;&quot;I demand a plan. The time for talk is over. Congress and the White House has to come up with something to stop this carnage.... Enough.&quot;</p><p>The videos are viewable at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.demandaplan.org/?nosplash=1\">DemandAPlan.org</a>. One features Tracy Lane, the mother of a student killed in the April 2007 massacre at Virginia Tech:</p><p>Bloomberg said that copies of all the videos would be sent to every member of the incoming 113th Congress.</p><p>Referring to the shootings in Newtown, Bloomberg said, &quot;If this moment passes into memory without action from Washington, it will be a stain&quot; on the country.</p><p>Bloomberg calls for&nbsp;three specific actions by Congress: 1) Pass the Fix Gun Checks Act, which would close the private sale loophole that allows more than 40% of gun sales to go through without a background check; 2) Pass an enforceable and effective assault weapons ban and a ban on high-capacity magazines; and 3) Make gun trafficking a felony.&nbsp;</p><p>&quot;Last night the president said he would use whatever power his office holds to address this violence, and I think it's critical that he do so,&quot; Bloomberg said.</p><p>&quot;We need immediate action... It should be at the top of their agenda.&quot;</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf5adf95cb356c029eb0b2\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T18:15:30.965Z\">1.15pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>The Guardian's Adam Gabbatt is <strong>in Fairfield, Connecticut,</strong>&nbsp;where memorial services for Noah Pozner, 6, are being held:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>White balloons lined the street outside the funeral home where the ceremony for Noah Pozner was to take place. The balloons bobbed around in the light breeze as dozens waited patiently to enter the building and pay their respects.</p><p>&quot;Our hearts are with you Noah,&quot; said a green sign pinned to a tree outside the Abraham L Green &amp; Son funeral home. Flowers and a brown teddy bear had been placed at the base of the tree.</p><p>Noah, 6, was the youngest victim of the Newtown shooting. An uncle described him as &quot;smart as a whip&quot; over the weekend. Noah's twin sister also attended Sandy Hook elementary, but was in a different classroom when the shooting began.</p><p>Guests walked slowly into the woodpanelled funeral home at around 12.30pm. The street was blocked off to the public as the Pozner family prepared to bid Noah farewell in private.</p><p>Outside the home, Rabbi Yakov Barros said people at the funeral were from &quot;all walks of life&quot;. He did not know the Pozner family but had travelled from the Catskills in upstate New York, where he is involved with the South Fallsburg Hebrew Association.</p><p>&quot;I'm here as a human being offering my love and support,&quot; Barros said. He said that the Pozner family had felt &quot;tremendous warmth&quot; that he had travelled to be at the funeral. &quot;The mother was very touched. She was crying at the fact I came.&quot;</p></blockquote></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T18:41:07.098Z\">at 1.41pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf5f9a95cb356c029eb0b3\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T18:08:26.573Z\">1.08pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>The <strong>police investigation</strong> of the Newtown assault will look at the crime, the weapons, the perpetrator and the timeline in exhaustive detail because people need to know what happened, Connecticut state police spokesman Paul Vance said.</p><p>Vance spoke at a briefing&nbsp;which he said will be the last for the day.&nbsp;</p><p>&quot;The answers are for the poor victims, the families, the people of Connecticut, that need to know and see a clear picture of what happened here,&quot; he said. &quot;There are many people... that have broken hearts over this. And we're gonna... paint a clear picture as to how and why this occurred.&quot;</p><p>Vance&nbsp;declined to say whether a computer was seized at the home of the gunman but he says the state has a computer crimes team. He said they're tracking every weapon &quot;and the clip, and all the weapons.&quot;</p><p>He says the two adults wounded in the shooting were wounded in the lower extremities.</p><p>&quot;There was no connection between the shooter and the school according to the school authorities here in Newtown,&quot; Vance said.</p><p>He says authorities are on heightened alert for threats to schools.</p><p>&quot;Anything whatsoever to do with school security... anything that's suspicious, anything that every remotely appears to be a [threat]... will be treated very seriously,&quot; he says.</p><p>He again asks for privacy for the families of victims.</p></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T18:19:40.605Z\">at 1.19pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf577095cb356c029eb0b1\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T17:33:36.968Z\">12.33pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p><strong>Gun control:</strong> After a high-profile shooting, the National Rifle Association, the voice of the gun industry, typically falls silent.</p><p>On Twitter, &quot;the model is to go silent for at least a day, depending on the scope of the tragedy,&quot;&nbsp;BuzzFeed's Andrew Kaczynski&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.buzzfeed.com/andrewkaczynski/how-the-nra-communications-twitter-handles-a-mass\">reports</a>.</p><p>The NRA has not tweeted since Friday morning. After the Aurora, Colorado movie theater shooting, the NRA <a href=\"http://www.buzzfeed.com/andrewkaczynski/how-the-nra-communications-twitter-handles-a-mass\">waited</a> 10 days before tweeting. After the mass shooting at the Sikh temple in Oak Creek, Illinois, the gun lobby waited one day.</p></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T17:39:37.261Z\">at 12.39pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf55fcb5799fbf77759f4f\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T17:27:24.815Z\">12.27pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>A moment of silence on the <strong>New York stock exchange</strong> this morning. Many workers on Wall Street commute from Connecticut.</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf53c495cb356c029eb0b0\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T17:17:56.692Z\">12.17pm <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p><strong>Gun control:</strong> who has the power to change the nation's gun laws in a way that will keep dangerous weapons out of the hands of potential killers?</p><p>The Washington Post's Aaron Blake <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2012/12/17/the-6-most-important-people-in-the-looming-gun-control-debate/\">identifies</a>&nbsp;six key figures in the anticipated debate on Capitol Hill over gun control. Any new bill would need the forceful support of the president and of powerful figures outside Washington such as New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg, the head of Mayors Against Illegal Guns.</p><p>But laws are passed by Congress, and without Congress, even an impassioned president cannot turn the pleas of a nation for public safety into a real barrier to unhinged people obtaining weapons made to kill humans.</p><p>Blake names Democrats in Congress who can help, including California Senator Dianne Feinstein, who &quot;said Sunday that&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2012/12/16/feinstein-will-introduce-assault-weapons-ban-in-senate/\">she will introduce a bill that would reinstate the assault weapons ban</a>, a law that lapsed in 2004 and hasn’t even made it to the floor of the Senate for renewal.&quot;</p><p>For any new gun legislation to become a reality, however, certain politicians will have to go against their perceived narrow political interests. These politicians generally fall into two groups: Republicans and Democrats living in &quot;red&quot; states.</p><p>Here are the Democrats Blake names:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p><strong>&nbsp;Senate Majority Leader Harry Reid (D-Nev.)</strong>: While it will be hard for any gun control bill to get GOP votes, it will also be very difficult to get votes from Senate Democrats who face reelection in red states in 2014. And they are legion. Sens. Max Baucus (D-Mont.), Mary Landrieu (D-La.), Mark Pryor (D-Ark.), Jay Rockefeller (D-W.Va.), Tim Johnson (D-S.D.) and Kay Hagan (D-N.C.) are all up in two years and will be very tough votes to get.&nbsp;And that doesn’t include Democratic senators in pro-gun swing states like Mark Udall in Colorado and Jeanne Shaheen in New Hampshire. In fact, Reid himself comes from a pro-gun state, and his supporters&nbsp;<a href=\"http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/08/27/for-reid-no-nra-endorsement/\">actively sought the NRA’s endorsement</a>&nbsp;in his 2010 reelection bid. If those red state Democrats vote for a bill, it will be in large part because of Reid’s leadership and because he took the leap with them.</p></blockquote><p>Read the <a href=\"http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2012/12/17/the-6-most-important-people-in-the-looming-gun-control-debate/\">full piece here</a>.</p></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T17:23:06.700Z\">at 12.23pm ET</time></p></div><div id=\"block-50cf4f7eb5799fbf77759f4d\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T16:59:42.808Z\">11.59am <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p><strong>The victims:</strong> Class photos and other pictures&nbsp;of some of the victims, including children, with short biographical notes <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/gallery/2012/dec/16/sandy-hook-shooting-victims-pictures#/?picture=401158467&amp;index=0\">are here</a>. Some of the victims' photos have not been released.</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf4d44b5799fbf77759f4b\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T16:50:12.836Z\">11.50am <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p><strong>Gun control:</strong> The Guardian's Simon Rogers uses data from the US&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.fbi.gov/about-us/cjis/nics/general-information/fact-sheet\">National Instant Criminal Background Check System</a>&nbsp;to get a sense for how many guns are sold in the United States. Sales are up:</p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>The figures show that there have been 16,808,538 applications in 2012 so far to the end of November. If they were approved, that would be&nbsp;<strong>enough weapons to stock member of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/nato\">Nato</a>'s armed forces nearly five times over.</strong>&nbsp;The system has received 156,577,260 applications since 1998 and the&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2012/jul/22/gun-homicides-ownership-world-list\">US has the highest gun ownership rate in the world</a>.</p></blockquote><p>Read the <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/datablog/2012/dec/17/how-many-guns-us?CMP=twt_gu\">full piece here</a>.</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf49a5b5799fbf77759f43\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T16:34:45.502Z\">11.34am <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p><strong>Newtown grieves.</strong> An AP photo montage of memorials in Newtown, with voiceover of townspeople talking about their grief.&nbsp;</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf48acb5799fbf77759f3f\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T16:30:38.752Z\">11.30am <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p>A lockdown this morning at schools in <strong>Ridgefield, Connecticut,</strong> within 10 miles of Newtown, has ended without incident.</p><p>Officials say a report of an armed man near a school has been resolved after the man was found to have an umbrella.</p><p>Libor Jany is a reporter at the Connecticut News-Times.</p><figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/ljanyNT/status/280706341666971648\"><blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>According to Ridgefield First Selectman Rudy Marconi, police have found the man and determined that he was, in fact, carrying an umbrella.</p>— Libor Jany (@ljanyNT) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/ljanyNT/status/280706341666971648\" data-datetime=\"2012-12-17T16:09:41+00:00\">December 17, 2012</a></blockquote></figure><p>Connecticut state police spokesman Paul Vance said earlier that the schools were locked down after a suspicious person was reported in the area &quot;that may in fact be armed.&quot;</p></div></div><div id=\"block-50cf402c95cba457d7011d69\" class=\"block\"><p class=\"block-time published-time\"><time datetime=\"2012-12-17T16:05:16.706Z\">11.05am <span class=\"timezone\">ET</span></time></p><div class=\"block-elements\"><p><strong>We're following developments in Newtown, Connecticut, as families of the victims of Friday's elementary school attack prepare funeral services to begin this afternoon, and continue through the next few days</strong>.&nbsp;</p><p>At 1pm, shiva and memorial services will be held for the youngest victim, Noah Pozner, who turned six last month. At the same time, a funeral will be held for his classmate Jack Pinto, six. A wake is scheduled this evening for James Mattioli, six, whose funeral will take place on Tuesday.</p><p>Here's a summary of where things stand:</p><p>• <strong>President Obama spoke at a memorial service</strong> in Newtown last night. &quot;We can't accept events like this as routine,&quot; he said.</p><p>• <strong>Most schools in the town are to reopen on Tuesday.</strong> Sandy Hook elementary is still a crime scene and is closed indefinitely, police said. Police called for privacy for the victims' families.</p><p>• <strong>Two adults wounded by gunfire in the attack are expected to recover</strong>, state police spokesman Paul Vance said. Earlier reports had one wounded.</p><p>• <strong>Police had &quot;no previous contact or concerns prior to this tragic event&quot; with the gunman</strong>, Adam Lanza, Vance said. He said he wasn't free to discuss details about the gunman but he asked anyone who may have treated Lanza or had information about him to contact police.</p><p>• <strong>Senator Joe Manchin, a West Virginia Democrat who has an 'A' rating from the National Rifle Association, said this morning that it's time to talk about the legality of assault rifles</strong>. “I dont know anyone in the sporting or hunting arena that goes out with an assault rifle,” Manchin told MSNBC’s Morning Joe. &quot;I don’t know anyone that needs 30 rounds in a clip to go hunting. I mean, these are things that need to be talked about.”</p></div><p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2012-12-17T16:15:59.923Z\">at 11.15am ET</time></p></div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/cont